00:56:17,077 --> 00:56:18,644
<i>What?</i>

991
00:56:18,645 --> 00:56:20,212
"Maybe it'll win some races
next year"?

992
00:56:20,213 --> 00:56:21,847
"Maybe it'll be a good stud"?

993
00:56:21,848 --> 00:56:23,482
Dead, it's worth $10 million,
rock.

994
00:56:23,483 --> 00:56:28,020
I'll take that
over a bunch of goddamn maybes.

995
00:56:28,021 --> 00:56:29,955
Look, you kill that horse,

996
00:56:29,956 --> 00:56:32,725
it's gonna look like
an insurance scam.

997
00:56:32,726 --> 00:56:33,926
You don't shoot it, rock.

998
00:56:33,927 --> 00:56:36,428
Jesus.

999
00:56:36,429 --> 00:56:37,429
All you need is some wires

1000
00:56:37,430 --> 00:56:38,731
and a couple
of alligator clips.

1001
00:56:38,732 --> 00:56:39,832
What is this,
amateur hour?

1002
00:56:39,833 --> 00:56:41,600
As long as you get the money.

1003
00:56:41,601 --> 00:56:44,136
I don't care how you do it.

1004
00:56:48,074 --> 00:56:50,642
[Crickets chirping]

1005
00:57:05,425 --> 00:57:07,593
Keep an eye
on that boy tonight.

1006
00:57:07,594 --> 00:57:10,429
He could have
a concussion.

1007
00:57:10,430 --> 00:57:12,631
Where's your girlfriend?

1008
00:57:12,632 --> 00:57:14,099
If you're talking about
Chrissie,

1009
00:57:14,100 --> 00:57:18,103
she hitched a ride
to town.

1010
00:57:18,104 --> 00:57:20,372
The hell
were you doing, Ray?

1011
00:57:20,373 --> 00:57:23,542
Why can't you
keep away from him?

1012
00:57:23,543 --> 00:57:25,678
I couldn't figure out
a way to do that tonight, Etta.

1013
00:57:29,683 --> 00:57:32,785
Pete's been talking about
going back to Texas.

1014
00:57:32,786 --> 00:57:35,688
I'm thinking
I might tag along.

1015
00:57:35,689 --> 00:57:37,189
I think you should.

1016
00:57:40,326 --> 00:57:41,794
So everyone just throws
in the towel.

1017
00:57:41,795 --> 00:57:44,630
Is that the way it is?

1018
00:57:44,631 --> 00:57:47,132
It's like you said,
Ray.

1019
00:57:47,133 --> 00:57:48,701
Money always wins.

1020
00:57:49,903 --> 00:57:52,705
[Thunder rumbling]

1021
00:57:59,979 --> 00:58:02,715
[Engine turns]

1022
00:58:10,256 --> 00:58:13,258
[Twangy guitar music]

1023
00:58:13,259 --> 00:58:21,200
# #

1024
00:58:24,070 --> 00:58:26,005
everything comes to an end.

1025
00:58:26,006 --> 00:58:28,007
That's what I keep hearing.

1026
00:58:28,008 --> 00:58:31,010
Thing is
to recognize it.

1027
00:58:31,011 --> 00:58:33,178
Sometimes stubborn
is the same as stupid.

1028
00:58:33,179 --> 00:58:36,749
I guess that all depends
on your point of view.

1029
00:58:38,885 --> 00:58:42,688
Guess maybe it does.

1030
00:58:42,689 --> 00:58:44,623
Well, I'm going to bed.

1031
00:58:44,624 --> 00:58:51,263
One way or another,
tomorrow's another day.

1032
00:59:04,077 --> 00:59:05,778
I'm real glad
Sonny didn't shoot you.

1033
00:59:08,248 --> 00:59:09,782
Yeah, me too.

1034
00:59:12,686 --> 00:59:15,254
Put on your coat, kid.

1035
00:59:15,255 --> 00:59:18,290
We're going for a ride.

1036
00:59:37,410 --> 00:59:38,577
Sonny.

1037
00:59:38,578 --> 00:59:39,578
Jesus.

1038
00:59:39,579 --> 00:59:41,080
You almost gave me
a heart attack.

1039
00:59:41,081 --> 00:59:44,083
Jim burns,
we met at woodbine once.

1040
00:59:44,084 --> 00:59:45,117
Fascinating.

1041
00:59:45,118 --> 00:59:46,518
Now get the hell
off my property.

1042
00:59:46,519 --> 00:59:49,688
I know
where your horse is.

1043
00:59:49,689 --> 00:59:51,457
Really?

1044
00:59:51,458 --> 00:59:53,325
[Laughs]

1045
00:59:53,326 --> 00:59:55,394
All right.

1046
00:59:55,395 --> 00:59:59,798
Step into my office.

1047
01:00:03,370 --> 01:00:04,970
If you want something done
around here,

1048
01:00:04,971 --> 01:00:10,342
you just
got to do it yourself.

1049
01:00:10,343 --> 01:00:12,311
Mm.

1050
01:00:34,768 --> 01:00:37,236
I wasn't aware I was running
a bed and breakfast here.

1051
01:00:37,237 --> 01:00:38,437
Oh, you mean the kid?

1052
01:00:38,438 --> 01:00:41,540
I figured he should stick around
a couple days

1053
01:00:41,541 --> 01:00:42,641
for safekeeping.

1054
01:00:42,642 --> 01:00:44,109
<i>I'm not talking</i>
<i>about the kid.</i>

1055
01:00:44,110 --> 01:00:45,844
I'm talking about
that big bay stallion

1056
01:00:45,845 --> 01:00:47,012
in my barn.

1057
01:00:47,013 --> 01:00:50,282
<i>I assume his name</i>
<i>is Jumping Jack Flash.</i>

1058
01:00:50,283 --> 01:00:52,685
I also will assume
you intend to trailer him

1059
01:00:52,686 --> 01:00:54,720
<i>back to Stanton Stables</i>
<i>this morning.</i>

1060
01:00:54,721 --> 01:00:56,488
I intend to trailer him over
at some point,

1061
01:00:56,489 --> 01:00:58,090
but not this morning.

1062
01:00:58,091 --> 01:00:59,658
First I got to set
something straight.

1063
01:00:59,659 --> 01:01:01,427
<i>The last time</i>
<i>you set something straight,</i>

1064
01:01:01,428 --> 01:01:02,928
<i>you went to jail</i>
<i>for two years.</i>

1065
01:01:02,929 --> 01:01:05,364
Maybe setting things straight
ain't exactly your strong suit.

1066
01:01:07,801 --> 01:01:09,768
<i>I won't have</i>
<i>that animal here.</i>

1067
01:01:09,769 --> 01:01:11,870
Son of a bitch just tried
to take my head off.

1068
01:01:11,871 --> 01:01:13,872
<i>(Paulie)</i>
<i>You got to give him a piece</i>
<i>of green apple.</i>

1069
01:01:21,081 --> 01:01:22,381
He likes green apples.

1070
01:01:26,219 --> 01:01:27,886
So that's it?

1071
01:01:27,887 --> 01:01:30,022
They drop the charges,
you return the horse?

1072
01:01:30,023 --> 01:01:33,959
Might be a little more
to it than that.

1073
01:01:33,960 --> 01:01:37,396
A man needs a project, Pete.

1074
01:01:37,397 --> 01:01:39,298
<i>Idle hands</i>
<i>are the devil's workshop.</i>

1075
01:01:39,299 --> 01:01:41,400
You're the one
told me that.

1076
01:01:45,472 --> 01:01:46,905
I need to learn
to keep my damn mouth shut.

1077
01:02:04,190 --> 01:02:06,925
[Hooves pounding]

1078
01:02:18,571 --> 01:02:20,205
You hear anything
about the Flash?

1079
01:02:20,206 --> 01:02:22,941
Yep, I hear he's
in the states.

1080
01:02:22,942 --> 01:02:24,543
I hear he's in Europe.

1081
01:02:24,544 --> 01:02:27,413
I hear he's in 5,000 cans
of Alpo dog food.

1082
01:02:27,414 --> 01:02:28,580
I hear all kinds
of things.

1083
01:02:28,581 --> 01:02:31,083
What's the insurance saying,
Jack?

1084
01:02:31,084 --> 01:02:32,985
Insurance isn't gonna pay
a claim on a horse

1085
01:02:32,986 --> 01:02:34,086
that's just missing.

1086
01:02:34,087 --> 01:02:35,187
If the animal
turns up dead,

1087
01:02:35,188 --> 01:02:36,188
they'll pay.

1088
01:02:36,189 --> 01:02:37,756
I hope they never pay.

1089
01:02:37,757 --> 01:02:39,191
I want the horse back.

1090
01:02:39,192 --> 01:02:41,326
I'll take the money
myself.

1091
01:02:41,327 --> 01:02:42,394
I know what you did,
Sonny.

1092
01:02:42,395 --> 01:02:43,395
You could be arrested.

1093
01:02:43,396 --> 01:02:44,396
It's forgery.

1094
01:02:44,397 --> 01:02:47,266
Hey, my father's sick.

1095
01:02:47,267 --> 01:02:49,635
I'm looking after
the family business.

1096
01:02:49,636 --> 01:02:51,704
You never looked after anybody
but yourself.

1097
01:02:51,705 --> 01:02:53,439
Rather rambunctious
is entered,

1098
01:02:53,440 --> 01:02:54,440
and he's gonna run,

1099
01:02:54,441 --> 01:02:56,475
so get over it.

1100
01:02:58,411 --> 01:02:59,745
Where is he, anyway?

1101
01:02:59,746 --> 01:03:01,947
He's in the barn.

1102
01:03:01,948 --> 01:03:04,383
That's where we keep
the horses, Sonny.

1103
01:03:04,384 --> 01:03:04,983
He's not ready to run.

1104
01:03:06,786 --> 01:03:07,886
Well,
I'll get him ready.

1105
01:03:07,887 --> 01:03:09,321
No,
you stay away from him.

1106
01:03:09,322 --> 01:03:11,223
I'll do it.

1107
01:03:11,224 --> 01:03:12,291
You stay away from him,

1108
01:03:12,292 --> 01:03:13,992
and you stay
the hell away from me.

1109
01:03:18,665 --> 01:03:20,933
Lighten up, Jack.

1110
01:03:20,934 --> 01:03:23,202
[Horse neighing]

1111
01:03:23,203 --> 01:03:24,970
<i>(Ray)</i>
<i>Look at those two horses.</i>

1112
01:03:24,971 --> 01:03:27,439
<i>Except for the mark</i>
<i>on Fast Market's forehead,</i>

1113
01:03:27,440 --> 01:03:29,975
they could be
out of the same mare.

1114
01:03:29,976 --> 01:03:31,243
And one's worth
a few thousand

1115
01:03:31,244 --> 01:03:33,812
and the other
a few million.

1116
01:03:33,813 --> 01:03:35,681
And the one worth millions

1117
01:03:35,682 --> 01:03:37,916
got the personality
of a damn cactus.

1118
01:03:37,917 --> 01:03:40,652
[Horse neighing]

1119
01:03:40,653 --> 01:03:43,522
I woke up this morning;
kid had all my chores done.

1120
01:03:45,358 --> 01:03:47,092
He's gonna put you
in a rocking chair, Pete.

1121
01:03:47,093 --> 01:03:48,827
You see the change
in him already?

1122
01:03:48,828 --> 01:03:51,530
<i>When he first got here,</i>
<i>he'd walk into a room</i>

1123
01:03:51,531 --> 01:03:53,499
<i>like he was apologizing</i>
<i>for something.</i>

1124
01:03:53,500 --> 01:03:54,933
<i>Now he don't.</i>

1125
01:03:54,934 --> 01:03:57,002
Hell, all I did was give him
an old hat,

1126
01:03:57,003 --> 01:03:58,537
and now he thinks
I'm the second coming.

1127
01:04:00,440 --> 01:04:02,341
<i>People like Sonny been telling</i>
<i>him his whole life</i>

1128
01:04:02,342 --> 01:04:04,643
he's no better
than a horse turd.

1129
01:04:04,644 --> 01:04:07,546
Well, I'm no saint,
and neither are you,

1130
01:04:07,547 --> 01:04:10,382
but I'd like to show him

1131
01:04:10,383 --> 01:04:11,817
that the Sonny Stantons
in the world

1132
01:04:11,818 --> 01:04:15,854
don't always come out
on top.

1133
01:04:15,855 --> 01:04:17,156
That's about
the longest speech

1134
01:04:17,157 --> 01:04:19,058
I ever heard
you make, Pete.

1135
01:04:19,059 --> 01:04:23,362
You're not gonna
make a habit of it, are you?

1136
01:04:23,363 --> 01:04:27,066
Nope.

1137
01:04:42,148 --> 01:04:45,084
[Horse neighing]

1138
01:04:47,520 --> 01:04:50,122
[Hooves thudding]

1139
01:05:06,039 --> 01:05:09,908
Good-looking horse
you got in the corral, Pete.

1140
01:05:09,909 --> 01:05:12,711
Yeah, he's just passing through,
that one.

1141
01:05:12,712 --> 01:05:15,147
Bet he is.

1142
01:05:15,148 --> 01:05:16,382
Now I know what kind
of a lunatic

1143
01:05:16,383 --> 01:05:21,653
would steal
a million-dollar racehorse.

1144
01:05:28,762 --> 01:05:31,663
[Car doors slam]

1145
01:05:36,069 --> 01:05:38,070
Hey, Pete.

1146
01:05:38,071 --> 01:05:39,538
We're looking
for Paulie Stanton.

1147
01:05:39,539 --> 01:05:40,906
We heard he might
be staying here.

1148
01:05:40,907 --> 01:05:43,042
He's here.

1149
01:05:43,043 --> 01:05:44,777
<i>And we have reason</i>
<i>to believe he's involved</i>

1150
01:05:44,778 --> 01:05:46,645
with that missing racehorse
from Stanton stables,

1151
01:05:46,646 --> 01:05:48,213
so we're gonna
have to search the premises.

1152
01:05:48,214 --> 01:05:50,749
I'm not in the habit
of boarding stolen horses.

1153
01:05:50,750 --> 01:05:52,618
Well, we'll take a look
just the same.

1154
01:05:52,619 --> 01:05:53,852
<i>(Chrissie)</i>
<i>Go and make your own</i>

1155
01:05:53,853 --> 01:05:54,853
<i>goddamn breakfast.</i>

1156
01:05:54,854 --> 01:05:56,055
<i>You don't own me.</i>

1157
01:05:56,056 --> 01:05:57,056
What are you looking at?

1158
01:05:57,057 --> 01:05:58,724
I'm taking a walk.

1159
01:05:58,725 --> 01:06:00,559
Anyone tries
to follow me,

1160
01:06:00,560 --> 01:06:02,194
<i>I'll knock you</i>
<i>on your damn ass.</i>

1161
01:06:06,099 --> 01:06:08,200
I think we'd better
have a look around.

1162
01:06:14,441 --> 01:06:17,609
<i>(Pete)</i>
<i>Sure you don't want to check</i>
<i>in the house?</i>

1163
01:06:17,610 --> 01:06:19,011
Horse might be setting
on the couch

1164
01:06:19,012 --> 01:06:21,714
watching <i>mister ed.</i>

1165
01:06:23,416 --> 01:06:25,584
Come on,
come on.

1166
01:06:25,585 --> 01:06:27,219
Heya.

1167
01:06:36,229 --> 01:06:38,330
We had to follow up,
Pete.

1168
01:06:38,331 --> 01:06:39,765
I understand.

1169
01:06:39,766 --> 01:06:40,733
Happy to help.

1170
01:06:43,403 --> 01:06:46,238
[Engine revs]

1171
01:07:06,926 --> 01:07:09,928
<i>[Chickens clucking]</i>

1172
01:07:09,929 --> 01:07:12,264
<i>Etta.</i>

1173
01:07:12,265 --> 01:07:13,265
Something I can do for you,
Pete?

1174
01:07:15,869 --> 01:07:17,870
I never figured you
to call the cops.

1175
01:07:17,871 --> 01:07:20,873
What are you talking about?

1176
01:07:20,874 --> 01:07:22,041
Ray didn't steal that horse.

1177
01:07:22,042 --> 01:07:23,642
<i>I never called</i>
<i>the goddamn cops.</i>

1178
01:07:23,643 --> 01:07:24,710
Do you think I'd turn him in?

1179
01:07:24,711 --> 01:07:26,478
You might.

1180
01:07:26,479 --> 01:07:28,881
You got an awful horn
in your gut over that boy.

1181
01:07:28,882 --> 01:07:29,882
<i>"Had," Pete.</i>

1182
01:07:29,883 --> 01:07:31,150
Past tense.

1183
01:07:31,151 --> 01:07:32,618
And I don't mean
to be rude,

1184
01:07:32,619 --> 01:07:35,054
but I got work to do.

1185
01:07:35,055 --> 01:07:36,388
You know, Etta,

1186
01:07:36,389 --> 01:07:37,990
there's more to this
than meets the eye.

1187
01:07:37,991 --> 01:07:40,859
<i>Ray's got a plan</i>
<i>that's gonna fix things.</i>

1188
01:07:40,860 --> 01:07:42,795
<i>Maybe this time</i>
<i>he'll get it right.</i>

1189
01:07:42,796 --> 01:07:46,231
<i>Or maybe he'll go</i>
<i>back to jail.</i>

1190
01:07:46,232 --> 01:07:50,969
Ray was the guy, Pete.

1191
01:07:50,970 --> 01:07:52,304
He was the guy,
and he fucked it up.

1192
01:07:55,008 --> 01:07:57,309
Well, I just thought
you should know.

1193
01:07:57,310 --> 01:07:59,278
Ray might not be back
this way again.

1194
01:08:00,680 --> 01:08:03,682
[Melancholy guitar music]

1195
01:08:03,683 --> 01:08:11,290
# #

1196
01:08:57,604 --> 01:09:00,039
hey.

1197
01:09:00,040 --> 01:09:01,240
So I was talking
to Pete...

1198
01:09:01,241 --> 01:09:02,241
you were talking
to Pete,

1199
01:09:02,242 --> 01:09:03,409
and now you're here
to tell me

1200
01:09:03,410 --> 01:09:04,410
what Pete
already told me

1201
01:09:04,411 --> 01:09:05,611
and what
you wouldn't tell me.

1202
01:09:05,612 --> 01:09:07,613
That it, Ray?

1203
01:09:07,614 --> 01:09:08,681
Well, it sounded better

1204
01:09:08,682 --> 01:09:10,182
when I was rehearsing
on the way in.

1205
01:09:10,183 --> 01:09:13,352
Yeah, I bet it did.

1206
01:09:13,353 --> 01:09:15,921
Etta, I let you down.

1207
01:09:15,922 --> 01:09:20,993
Yeah, you're fucking right,
you let me down.

1208
01:09:20,994 --> 01:09:24,997
But I let you down too,
so let's call it even?

1209
01:09:26,900 --> 01:09:27,499
I can be happy with that.

1210
01:09:30,937 --> 01:09:33,072
Okay, if I ask you

1211
01:09:33,073 --> 01:09:34,807
what you're gonna do
with that horse,

1212
01:09:34,808 --> 01:09:36,041
am I gonna regret it?

1213
01:09:36,042 --> 01:09:38,344
I'd say there's a good
possibility of that.

1214
01:09:38,345 --> 01:09:41,013
[Laughs]

1215
01:09:42,682 --> 01:09:44,516
What are you gonna do
with that horse?

1216
01:09:59,632 --> 01:10:01,767
If this is about the Flash,
forget it.

1217
01:10:01,768 --> 01:10:05,504
Somebody stole him back.

1218
01:10:05,505 --> 01:10:08,040
Can't trust anybody
these days.

1219
01:10:12,545 --> 01:10:14,880
We stole him.

1220
01:10:14,881 --> 01:10:16,048
What do you know
about it, idiot?

1221
01:10:17,584 --> 01:10:20,019
Keep the name-calling
to yourself.

1222
01:10:20,020 --> 01:10:21,387
What's this about?

1223
01:10:21,388 --> 01:10:23,322
<i>It's about getting out</i>
<i>of a bad situation.</i>

1224
01:10:23,323 --> 01:10:24,056
Don't ask questions.

1225
01:10:28,361 --> 01:10:29,695
I want to know
what's going on.

1226
01:10:29,696 --> 01:10:34,566
Don't ask questions,
Dean.

1227
01:10:41,474 --> 01:10:44,476
[Grooving blues music]

1228
01:10:44,477 --> 01:10:52,084
# #

1229
01:11:07,467 --> 01:11:09,101
[phone rings]

1230
01:11:12,672 --> 01:11:14,039
Yeah?

1231
01:11:14,040 --> 01:11:16,342
<i>[Man on phone]</i>
<i>Reginald "Sonny" Stanton?</i>

1232
01:11:16,343 --> 01:11:17,609
Yeah.

1233
01:11:17,610 --> 01:11:20,179
<i>Detective Frank Hamer,</i>
<i>O.P.P.</i>

1234
01:11:20,180 --> 01:11:22,281
<i>There's been a complaint</i>
<i>lodged against you</i>

1235
01:11:22,282 --> 01:11:27,052
